    <div xlink:href="41467_2019_9499_Article_Equ4.gif" position="anchor" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   </div>
  </div>For 
  <span class="italic">χ</span> = 1, the Kuznets-relevant income equals the true (modeled) per capita income in the region-time pair, producing our default best-guess emission intensity factors. Changing 
  <span class="italic">I</span>(
  <span class="italic">χ</span>) allows us to explore assumptions of more or less stringent autonomous air quality policies: we can speed up (
  <span class="italic">χ</span> &gt; 1) or slow down (
  <span class="italic">χ</span> &lt; 1) the decrease in emission intensities over time accordingly.
 </p>
 <p id="Par54" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Supplementary Figure 
  <a rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media" href="#MOESM1">5</a> shows the baseline (pre-mitigation) level of emissions by region and time under the default of 
  <span class="italic">χ</span> = 1, where the Kuznets-relevant income equals the true (modeled) income.
 </p>
